# Swift / SwiftUI / SwiftData Patterns

## Architecture rules
- MVVM — keep business logic OUT of Views
- ViewModels are `@Observable` classes (Swift 5.9+ macro, not `ObservableObject`)
- Use pure functions for all training algorithms — no side effects, easy to unit test
- Keep files small and focused; one type per file as a default
- Avoid massive ViewModels — split by responsibility

## SwiftUI conventions
- Prefer simple SwiftUI over custom abstractions
- No premature optimization
- Large touch targets (minimum 44 × 44 pt, prefer 56 pt for primary actions)
- Bottom sheets over full-screen navigation flows
- No modal spam — every presented sheet must have a clear dismiss path
- Logging a set must take < 3 taps / < 3 seconds end-to-end
- Never block UI with a loading spinner unless unavoidable

## SwiftData
- `@Model` classes live in `Core/Models/`
- Use `@Query` in Views for reactive data binding
- Autosave enabled; never require an explicit "Save" button
- Preserve unfinished sessions across app restarts
- No network dependency at the persistence layer

## Training engine (Core/Algorithms/)
- Percentage-based progression
- RPE tracking
- Fatigue scoring + deload triggers
- Progression blocks
- All logic is pure Swift functions with no UIKit/SwiftUI imports
- This is the most critical layer — unit-test everything here

## Testing priorities (highest → lowest)
1. Progression calculations
2. Fatigue scoring
3. Percentage math
4. Deload trigger logic
5. Workout generation
6. UI tests (lowest priority)

## Swift 6 concurrency
- Prefer `@MainActor` on ViewModels
- Use `async/await` for any deferred work
- Avoid global mutable state; pass dependencies explicitly

## Naming
- Models: noun, singular (`WorkoutSession`, `LiftSet`)
- ViewModels: `<Feature>ViewModel`
- Services: `<Domain>Service`
- Views: `<Feature>View` or `<Feature>Screen`
